"Bauer E., Petoukhov V., Ganopolski A., Eliseev A.V.","Climatic response to anthropogenic sulphate aerosols versus well-mixed greenhouse gases from 1850 to 2000 AD in CLIMBER-2",2008,"Tellus, Series B: Chemical and Physical Meteorology","60 B","1",,"82","97",,,10.1111/j.1600-0889.2007.00318.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38349014019&partnerID=40&md5=6630cacea54c73b964e00fcb7c44855a","Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, PO Box, 60 12 03, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; A.M. Obukhov Institute of Atmospheric Physics, RAS, Moscow, Russian Federation","Bauer, E., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, PO Box, 60 12 03, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; Petoukhov, V., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, PO Box, 60 12 03, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; Ganopolski, A., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, PO Box, 60 12 03, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; Eliseev, A.V., A.M. Obukhov Institute of Atmospheric Physics, RAS, Moscow, Russian Federation","The Earth system model CLIMBER-2 is extended by a scheme for calculating the climatic response to anthropogenic sulphur dioxide emissions. The scheme calculates the direct radiative forcing, the first indirect cloud albedo effect, and the second indirect cloud lifetime effect induced by geographically resolved sulphate aerosol burden. The simulated anthropogenic sulphate aerosol burden in the year 2000 amounts to 0.47 TgS. The best guesses for the radiative forcing due to the direct effect are -0.4 W m-2 and for the decrease in short-wave radiation due to all aerosol effects -0.8 W m-2. The simulated global warming by 1 K from 1850 to 2000 caused by anthropogenic greenhouse gases reduces to 0.6 K when the sulphate aerosol effects are included. The model's hydrological sensitivity of 4%/K is decreased by the second indirect effect to 0.8%/K. The quality of the geographically distributed climatic response to the historic emissions of sulphur dioxide and greenhouse gases makes the extended model relevant to computational efficient investigations of future climate change scenarios. © 2007 The Authors Journal compilation © 2007 Blackwell Munksgaard.",,"aerosol; climate change; global warming; greenhouse gas; radiative forcing; shortwave radiation; sulfur dioxide; sulfur emission",,,,,,"Albrecht, B.A., Aerosols, cloud microphysics, and fractional cloudiness (1989) Science, 245, pp. 1227-1230; Bauer, E., Claussen, M., Brovkin, V., Huenerbein, A., Assessing climate forcings of the Earth system for the past millennium (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett., 30, p. 1276; Bauer, E., Claussen, M., Analyzing seasonal temperature trends in forced climate simulations of the past millennium (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett., 33, pp. L02702; Boucher, O., Schwartz, S.E., Ackerman, T.P., Anderson, T.L., Bergstrom, B., Intercomparison of models representing direct shortwave radiative forcing by sulfate aerosols (1998) J. Geophys. Res., 103, pp. 16979-16998. , co-authors; Boucher, O., Pham, M., History of sulfate aerosol radiative forcings (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29, p. 1308; Brohan, P., Kennedy, J.J., Harris, I., Tett, S.F.B., Jones, P.D., Uncertainty estimates in regional and global observed temperature changes: A new data set from 1850 (2006) J. Geophys. Res., 111, pp. D12106; Brovkin, V., Bendtsen, J., Claussen, M., Ganopolski, A., Kubatzki, C., Carbon cycle, vegetation and climate dynamics in the Holocene: Experiments with the CLIMBER-2 model (2002) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 16, p. 1139. , co-authors; Charlson, R.J., Langner, J., Rodhe, H., Leovy, C.B., Warren, S.G., Perturbation of the northern hemisphere radiative balance by backscattering from anthropogenic sulfate aerosols (1991) Tellus, 43 AB, pp. 152-163; Charlson, R.J., Schwartz, S.E., Hales, J.M., Cess, R.D., Coackley, J.A., Climate forcing by anthropogenic aerosols (1992) Science, 255, pp. 423-430. , co-authors; Chuang, C.C., Penner, J.E., Taylor, K.E., Grossman, A.S., Walton, J.J., An assessment of the radiative effects of